annotation: a standard reaction against the Philidor: Black cannot allow dxe5...
no fear, for b5-b4: we take over the center...
hard to follow: Black had several better moves...
a bit brisky, for the White King: but it works...
finishing development: apart from solving the threat of Be4...
White has done enough damage: this is stronger than Be4...
Black acknowledges the problem: Nxe7+ wins another tempo, and pawn f5 is invulnerable; because Whites' next move, will always be Bg4...
also here, there were better solutions...
here Black resigned: White is about to rip open the Black Kings' wing...
But I found this a fun game!
I sac a piece for two pawns and an attack. My attack doesn't break through, but I gain another pawn and manage to win the ending.
So I aim for an open Sicilian.
He seems to be heading for the same.
But what is this? My opponent (who doesn't state a sex) offers a transposition to a Benoni type position.
I take - I am looking for quick development and keeping the black king in the centre.
Black prevents the further advance of the d pawn.
I am trying to make it hard for black to develop.
He hits the bishop, but the e6 square is now weak.

Black attacks the bishop again. What would you play here dear reader? Fritz recommends 12. Be3. This position was reached in a Gameknot game kiede (1698) vs. vl007 (1762) where 12. Bg3 was played and white won after Qb6
13.	b3	Kd7
14.	Nbd2	Nh6
15.	Nc4	Qd8
16.	Qd3	Kc7
17.	Rxe7+	Bd7
18.	Bxd6+	Kc8
19.	Qe3	
However in this game I was not using the opening databases. I couldn't resist sacrificing on g5 - I spent most of my time thinking about which piece to sacrifice. If you had to sacrifice on g5, which piece would you use?
I take. Fritz gives slight advantage to black now (+0.2)
There is some logic in this, in breaking the pin, but perhaps Kd7 as in kiede (1698) vs. vl007 (1762) was better.
Of course! Fritz gives it as +3.25 to white now.
What would you play here dear reader? Black threatens Bxg5 of course!
I completely missed 15. Rxe7! which wins a knight, as after 15......Nxe7 16. Bh6+ white wins the rook on h8 and ends up a knight up. Thanks to Fritz for pointing that out!
Black logically give the king some cover.
With ideas of doubling on the e file and/or moving the rook into action to f3 or g3. Fritz prefers Ne4.
And I get mine into action.

I think this is a mistake. Time to either drive my queen back with Rf5 or to move his other rook to b8 and attack b2. A problem with putting the bishop on this square is that the protection of d6 is blocked.
So I try to exploit that, with an attack on d6.
Heading for the weak e6 square. Fritz now puts white as 0.5 up.
So in it goes. A real family fork, attacking king, queen and rook.
Of course black has to take.
I take back. attacking the knight.
The best way, leading to another exchange.

Forcing an ending where I have three pawns for the knight. Fritz prefers 24.....Nf4 25. Rxf6 Nxh5 26. Rxd6 Nf4 27. g3 Nd3 and the black knight is more active than in the game, but I don't think it makes much difference. the way Fritz suggests gives me two passed pawns, but this way, only one.
Fritz prefers 27. g3 keeping the knight out, and leaving white 0.34 ahead.
Fritz prefers Kf6, but it makes little difference.
I give my king a flight square.
Black goes after my d pawn.
I go after the black c pawn.
Black checks. I am not convinced these checks are good - they just seem to drive my king up the board to where I want him to go.
King moves away. Here was one of the few times black paused and thought. I'd guess my opponent was looking at taking on h2 and worked out that there wasn't time. Fritz like 37...g4 here.
My king now is in a good attacking position.
So the knight comes back to help defend.
Pawn advances, but Fritz thinks it is the wrong one, and prefers 40. a4
Rook is now attacked. Fritz actually prefers a7, but I thought this was more logical, keeping the king near the pawn.
So rook flees to the corner.

Fritz prefers 42. Kb7 but I was running short of time, and not sure whether I was trying to win or draw this. I saw the combination which lost my d pawn, but exchanged rooks, and then I saw that I could exchange black's remaining pawn and have at least a draw.
But I am going to play h4 next move and exchange the last black pawn.
The black king comes up. Fritz gives this as a mistake.
Rather random knight move. Fritz is also critical of it.
I wasn't using an endgame database, but I managed to find the only move to win, according to it!
Most moves win, but this is the quickest.
Here I missed the quicker win 50. f4!
Protecting the pawn and attacking the knight.
Knight returns to the square its colleague started on.

Attacking the knight. Kc7 is even stronger, but this was enough to force black to resign. Thanks for reading, I hope you found it enjoyable and educational. Please rank the annotation with the star system and leave a comment or two to let me know how I am doing. Until next time dear reader!
Black is losing a decisive tempo...
all kinds of pieces en prise...
a standard error, in the Giuoco Piano...
Qb3, usually leads to a draw...

Hi everyone!

So in my last annotated game against the Caveman, Coach Ion concluded that Fou Leblanc had let Henry down a bundle by moving to the wrong square.  In this game I find myself in another piece ending and with both sides having light square bishops.  In the endgame I end up being the player with the pawn plus against my fellow Class A opponent.  But will this give Fou Leblanc the opportunity to make amends and to help Henry bring the game to a satisfactory conclusion? Well, you'll just have to read on.
1. ….. d5 - white kicks off with the Reti Opening and I make the most common response to it.
3. c4 - transposing into a Queen's Gambit.
5. Bxc4 - and now it is a QGA.
6. ….. e6 - preparing to develop Fou Lenoir.
9. ……. 0-0 - both kings tuck themselves away on the kingside.
10. Rc1?! - this move starts off some explosive activity in the centre and this is where I end up with the pawn plus.
14. ……. Qd2 - after a whirlwind of captures and exchanges Glenda takes evasive action.
15. Bd3 - clever.  If Glenda should play Qxc3?? then Bxh7+ loses her to the WQ.  So on the next turn she retreats to h6.
19. ….. Bb5 - but Fou Leblanc is able to escape with a threat.
20. Rfc1 - of which white parries strongly.
22. …… Qd8 - trying to trade my way out of passivitis but white declines the Queen trade.
24. ……. Qxc8 - but there is a rook trade.
26. Rc7 - again very nasty, but Glenda now puts the WK in Old Matey's shadow.
29. ……. Qb2 - taking control of the a1-h8 diagonal before the WQ does.
31. Rxc3 - now the queens have finally been traded off.  I am still a pawn up, but will it be enough to win in what is now an endgame?  We shall see.
33. Rb3 - everything is being concentrated on the weakie pawn on b4.
34. ….. Bxd3 - and now we have that bishop ending.  Now Henry needs to get to the pawn on b4 before the WK does.
44. f5 - trying to create a block.  I am, however, prepared to be very patient.
46. …..Kc6 - Henry continues his mission to try and gobble up that juicy looking b4 pawn.
50. ….. Kxa5 - however, after getting nowhere we have a pawn trade.  I do at least get a passer on the e column, but will I be able to push it?  We shall see.
53. ……. Kc2 - Henry is now trying to get over to the kingside so that he can perhaps take off one or both of the remaining white pawns and shepherd one of my kingside pawns through to Glendadom.
55. ……. Ke1 - these checks have just driven Henry ever closer to the white pawns.

58. …… Bf3 - now Fou Leblanc is doing well.  I now plan to exchange my e pawn for white's g4 pawn.  I will then put Henry on f2 and that will give my g pawn a protected path to Glendadom.  After I took the pawn on g4 on the next turn, white realised my plan and waved the white flag.  Good work in the end by Fou Leblanc.  Wheew!
always a tell tale: this is going to be nice...
I love it, when they have no clue...
Sicilian mob style: take over the Queens' wing...
If 28...Bxf4 29. c7 and the pawn promotes for sure...
the start, of a very wrong idea...
but they do not understand chess...
here, this bot resigned: not too soon...
most people try Qa5, d4, to be followed by Bd2: this one has more sense...
the only active Black piece, is going for grabs...
makes you wonder, who teaches this guys chess...
this is going to be nice...
we do not even bother, to take Rf8...

And, he plays the Sicilian which is how I answer.  Coach Stockel said that in a tournament, about two years ago, they played the Sicilian.  17 moves were all analyzed, but then, someone played a move that was not analyzed before and turned out to be very good.  That's why a lot of GM's stopped playing it, recently.
Of course, I'm used to everything up until right here.  As the first defense that I had to learn was the Sicilian Nadjorf.
Although, I think Jack said sometime ago, that this is the main response to 5...a6.

But, things become interesting as Giuseppe is threatening to exchange B for N which favors him.  The logic behind GM Susan Polgar advising me to not exchange B for N without a good reason is because of something I recently found out.  They say that B and N are both worth 3 points.  But, that's no true for the B.  The N is, but a B is worth 3.5 points, according to what a GM told Jack.
Having said that, I would've played 7.Bd2 since Giuseppe will reattack.
I knew that all of that was coming.  But, I guess that this is a better place for the DSB then on d2.

Guiuseppe continues with his development and prepares to castle, as would I.  One thing is for sure that after fianchettoing, bringing the B out like this is generally what you want to do, as I recently learned from Jack.  The reason being is that you don't waste a tempo with ...e6 or ...e5 to get it out.
I would've continued developing and prepared to castle with 10.Bd3  But, Laura finds a very clever move and goes right after Giuseppe's N.

And, she brings her Q in action.  Her goal is to castle long.  I, however, would developed the Bf1 and prepared to castle short.  But, this has got to better.  And, I see why given that a pawn near has advanced.  So, castling Q side is safer.
Meanwhile, Giuseppe continues developing.  So, he goes on the other side.  He, on the other hand, will castle short.  Castling on opposite wings makes things very interesting.

But, Giuseppe, forces and exchange, first.  Personally, I wouldn't have done that just because I would not be ready to exchange yet.  As I'd be doing it just because it's possible which is not a good reason, as kenneth_fiore_3 has stressed to me.  But, there's something about that which makes it good here.
I would've gone on the offense with a masked battery, by moving the Ne5.  But, I like this move just as much.

Centralizing her N.  And, this is where I start to see a draw coming since both sides are well developed and centralized.  In addition, this move poses a nasty threat.  Although it won't win anything, forking on b6 would force Giuseppe to exchange his undeveloped B.

Contrary to before, I don't see the point of this move.  I do believe that Giuseppe played this for a pawn chain, but I know there's more to it then just that.  In this position, I would've gone on the offense with 14...e6

I am shocked that Laura plays this given that a B is usually worth more.  On the other hand, there are times where it is necessary to exchange B for N.  I guess this is one of them.  However, I didn't see an immediate threat Giuseppe's N.

Going for a Q exchange which is what I also would've done since Giuseppe's Q is starting to become a menace.  In addition, this will also fork and force black to exchange his undeveloped B.  It's right here that I figure out the likeliness that this is, in fact, a draw.  It's not clear cut, yet, but I begin to realize just how difficult it would be for Giuseppe to win.
Going after the N in response to the fork.
Afterwhich, Laura plans to complete her development with this fianchetto.

I don't see the point behind this move since it is not a passed pawn.  That might be his goal.  On the other hand, I'm not so sure what I would've done.  But, I'd probably answer with 19...Rc5, followed by 20...Rc8 to attack c2 twice.

This is very interesting.  As I would've completed the fianchetto with 20.Bg2, but Laura still completes her development with this move.  Believe it or not, I like this move even better since this threatens to attack with 21.Bg4  In fact, that's why white played this since Giuseppe will stop that threat with his next move.

Laura goes for a R exchange which is what I also would've done.  The idea is that the R is menace, so get it out of it.  But, with this exchange, I now know that it's a draw.  It's not if but when.  I thought it would take longer, but it's around the corner.
Making an advancement of his pawn.  I, however, would've held off and gone on the offense with 22...Bd4
Having said that, I like Laura's response.  Not seeing the point behind the last move, this is also what I would've done.

But, I can see it here, however, since not two, but three of Giuseppe's pawns are now connected.  So, with 3 against 3, it does poes as a real threat of breaking through.  By breaking through, I mean advancing, exchanging pawns, and getting an unstoppable passed pawn that would promote.
But, Laura puts a stop to that which is what I also would've done.

Rather then exchange and allow a passed pawn, Giuseppe blocks it here.  And, this is how I also would've answered.  After that, given that it's Laura's move, Giuseppe agrees that noone can win and offers a draw.  Laura agrees with that conclusion and accepts the offer.
I dunno why I didn’t a1 = Q now...
I start off normally, as does black.
But, Tom plays something different which I have seen before, The Philidor's Defense.
So, I chose the, natural, response.  And, it stays in book, until the 5th move.

As it's almost noon, and being concerned that the Senior Center will kick everyone out of the club before we can finish the game, I decide to do something different.  I break the general opening guidelines by getting my Q out early.  Now when studying these openings, Jack emphasized that pieces need to be developed.  In fact, I went wrong against him by failing to do that, even though, the Q was not early.  My goal here is to trick Tom into making a mistake by not advancing his d pawn.  If I can capture on d6, the pin will be right there.  I generally don't go for tricks but was concerned about adjourning early.  This usually isn't an issue since I generally have to be out by noon, due to the work schedule.  However, I was off on Friday since I got called the day prior.  And, I'd rather lose a game and play poorly then not be able to finish it.  But, I now know for next time that the Senior Center does not kick anyone out, if they're late.  Were it not for that, I would've continued developing with 5.Bd3.
Of course, Tom does not fall for it and protects.

So, I pull back to the original square.  Of course, my concentration goes back on development.  But, it's kind of late for that now because of Tom's next move.  I felt that it was inaccurate since I hit, but he has a surprise waiting for me.

And, it's with this move since Tom threatens to fork and win a R.  Jack showed a similar example on the same square with the Guaco Piano, as after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Be7 is best to prevent advancing the d pawn, followed by Ng5 which would lead to the same type of fork.  Keeping that in mind, Tom makes the threat.  This leaves my K, somewhat exposed, because of what's about to happen.

As this is my only option, and when Tom takes, the only way to protect is remove the weakest pawn on the chess board which, already, gives black an advantage.  This is another reason as to why developing earlier and not bringing the Q out early was better.  What will hope, as noted earlier, is that one can stay late without being forced to adjourn.  That is, if I'm off that day.
Tom takes advantage of my weakness by pinning.  I thought about what to do here.

I had considered breaking the pin in a more calm matter with 10.Be2.  But, the only reason I'd do this is because Coach Stockel said that it's usually better to break the pin with the B.  On the other hand, kenneth_fiore_3 said that I needed to give more thought then just that.  For a while, I hadn't, until other commentators said that it's generally better to do it in a more aggressive way.  After careful consideration, I thought that doing it more aggressively was better to gain two tempii.  10.Be2 wouldn't have done it since Tom could just leave his B on g4.  Was it worth it, though?  I think not, and do believe that breaking it more passively was better here.  As this is bound to give Tom a space advantage.  It will further weaken my K side since I use the other pawn, after 10...Bh5.  That wasn't just tempo but getting a pawn chain which was meaningless.  Thus, I should've given that more thought, as well.

As I thought that 11...Bg6, and that was the only thing that came to mind.  But, I missed this move.  Although the fork is not that effective, the long term results make it so.  As now, I'm bound to have two bad pawn on the h file, and my K will be even more exposed.  Plus, it will take me even longer to continue developing my pieces, thus, increasing Tom's space advantage even further.

? I could've taken the N, but I know that it's usually better to take the B.  In fact, I mentioned to Jack GM Susan Polgar emphasized that I shouldn't exchange my B for N without a good reason.  And, he said that new studies now show that N's are still worth 3 points, but the B is 3.5 points.  That's the first thing I kept in mind here, but once again, didn't think about it even more.  And, I should've given that more thought since Tom is going to win a pawn now.  Thus, 13.Rxf1 was the way to go.
Knowing what I've done, I go right after Tom's N.
And, I go for something crazy, knowing that he can't capture.  My plan here is 16.Ne5, followed by 17.exf7+ with a dangerous threat against black.
But, Tom puts a stop to that.
So, I start a different which is going after Tom's Nf5.
Not surprisingly, Tom completes his development.

So, I go right after Tom's N.  The idea isn't winning it, but rather, that he's forced to retreat which would allow me to win back a pawn.  But, Tom puts a stop to that with his next move.  When that happens, I complete my development, once and for all.
Going after my R, which I'm about to protect.

Tom was going after my K since he might be trying to build his army with both his N's and Q.  I saw a similar pattern with bhidragon, along with other games.  In fact, there was even one with Susan Polgar.  The idea is building an army of attacking forces against it.

So, I attempt to stop it by trying to exchange N's.  Ken said that you shouldn't exchange without a good reason.  But, he also showed me how he won his first game against me by not exchanging.  That's the first thing I kept in mind here, since Tom has just a much pressure.  Like before, I try to trick him into making a bad choice and exchanging which would be in my favor.  Thus, it is now Hope Chess.  But, it's at the wrong time since this gives him what he wants which is an overwhelming amount of pressure against the monarch.
At first, I didn't think so since my first thought was that this is a terrible blunder which allows me to win his N.  But, that's not so, due to his Q.  And, I'm not going to lose a R for N, either.
? So, I respond by attacking his N a second time.  But, this is a mistake that will allow Tom to win another pawn.  Much better was 21.Qe3.
It was a little noisy on and off but not too bad, until now.  Had it been a little quieter, I would've answered with 22.Kd1 to prevent a check.

This is where the noise starts to get overwhelming and does not end.  But, according to Master Nathan A Resika it loses right away.  Best was, of course, 23.Nxe4.  And, I didn't refuse to play it to avoid liquidation either.  In fact, that's what I thought I had done since it was notated.  But, what's to come here is exactly how it happened.  And, from that, I discovered that I overlooked it.  Usually, I wonder why, and it takes time to figure out.  But, from what I explained above, it was, indeed, the noise.  What's more is that Nathan Resika commented in the end of the game.  I thought he said failing to take the R was where I lost.  But, Tom didn't have a R en-prise.  What Nathan was alluding to was the N on this move.  If I didn't have the distraction, nothing else would've come into consideration, besides 23.Nxe4  Now, I generally won't disagree with a Master, but Nathan was wrong here.  Failing to take is not where I go wrong, at all.  The next move is where it happened.  However, the reason was probably noise because it does not go away, as the staff are preparing the room for others.
?? Having said that, this is where it happens.  There were only 3 options.  The other 2 were 24.Kg3 or 24.Kf2.   Either one would've kept me in the game, but this leads to an immediate mate.

I thought that Tom's best move was 24...Qe4+??, with which, I was prepared to exchange Q's.  But, that move would've lost for black since I can take with the N.  However, this is the only time where Nathan comments during the game, and he tells Tom to look at my intentions and weaknesses.  And, that's what helped black to find this mate.
Najdorfs' contribution to the Sicilian: prevent interference on b5...
White is still oblivious: but Black is taking over the Queens' wing...
and again, White disappeared: he timed out...
no idea, what Black is building in there: we let him be, for a while...
time, to do something about it...
let him have it, for a while...
for some reason, Black timed out here...
taken care of, a long time ago...
clearly posing a problem: White is getting out of moves...
here, I resigned: with a vengeance in my heart...
do not try this at home: best is Bxd2, Nxd2, 0-0...
Black loses a piece: he resigned...
the French defense: always good for breakfast..
this Black Queen is clearly on some mission...
Black is not getting anywhere soon...
like taking candy, from a child...
Black resigned: his Queen is caught...
3.d4 exd4 4.Nxd4 is more usual, but there's no reason this can't be played.

Presumably played to prevent my playing 4.Ng5 at some point, this is not good for a couple of reasons. It hands White a tempo, which Black can hardly afford so early in the game, and it weakens the K-side pawns unnecessarily and could become a target, as in fact happens.
I carry on with the usual moves against the Philidor...

One of the problems with the Philidor Defence is that it rather limits the scope of the dark-squared Bishop. Of course, Philidor's whole chess philosophy was that the pieces belonged behind the pawns, but we've moved on a little since his day. On the plus side, had Black defended the e-pawn with 2...Nc6 we'd be looking at the Scotch with the option for White of doubling Black's pawns with Nxc6. Even so, White is already building up a strong centre, which is probably why the computer prefers 6...c5, driving away the centrally placed Knight instead of getting the Bishop out.
Both sides get their Kings to safety.
Now I have all four minor pieces developed, in contrast to Black's already passive position.

Not sure there's much point to this, but Black wants to develop his Knight and doesn't want to go to c6 in case I double his pawns with 9.Nxc6. 8...Nd7 blocks the light-squared Bishop, hence, I imagine, this move.
Rather opens up a diagonal to the King, but adds support to the e-pawn and gives White a tempo, since the Bishop must now move again.
It's probably better, having drawn out the f-pawn, to retreat back along the c8-h3 diagonal, but I guess Black wants to keep the f-pawn pinned.
However, it's a pin easily removed. And now I have two pieces eyeing that dubiously advanced h-pawn.

Since Black has, in drawing out the f-pawn, ensured that the e-pawn is defended, this doubling of attack isn't especially threatening. Also, the Bishop isn't actually defended here, since Black's f-pawn is pinned, something that will have consequences later. Possibly Black intends to tuck the Bishop away on h7?
Even so, I add to the e-pawn's defence. Perhaps 11.Rfe1 would have been more logical, but this gets my final piece into the game nicely.
Dubious. Not played to release the f-pawn, which is pinned, but to add to the defence of g5, I suspect. But it would have been better to get the other Knight out instead.

I was tempted to open the defence up with a sacrifice 12.Bxh6 gxh6 13.Qxh6, but it didn't really go anywhere. Instead I attack the pawn yet again, and the dark-squared Bishop into the bargain. But I could have attacked it with 12.Nd5 instead; this just gives Black the chance to dispose of his rather problematic Bishop.
He's doubled my pawns, though it remains to be seen whether this pawn is a threat or a weakness.
Finally Black's remaining minor piece joins the game.
Over ambitious, perhaps - once again I am eyeing the sacrifice on h6 and want to follow up with Rg5, but it looks a little suspect.
I haven't really got time anyway; not for the first time I neglect the fact that Black can move too, and now he's challenging the dangerous diagonal.
I don't feel I have much choice!
I's like to play 16.Rg4 but 16...Ne5 would rather scupper things. At least here I am preventing the c-pawn from moving at present.
Black goes a little astray now, with a couple of rather pointless moves. This attacks the Bishop, but it's easily moved away...
In fact it might have been prudent to play this earlier. Even so, Black has rather evened the game up a little.
I still can't figure out this one. Why? Maybe it's juat a waiting move, to see what I do next?
So, now that Ne5 isn't a possibility, I continue with my plan.
Black covers g7 and attacks my loose pawn. He probably needed to get the King out of the line of fire on h8.
I could, it seems, have played 19.h4 here, and Black's really in trouble. But I wanted to defend the pawn

Black wants to block off the diagonal against the King by advancing his d-pawn, but really hasn't got time. Plus this leaves the Knight on b6 undefended, something I quite missed, being preoccupied with when to play h4. 20.Qb4 seems to take the Queen away from the action.
So I play h4, a move later than I could have played it, but it's still very dangerous.

Black gets to block the diagonal but has to give up the Knight. The alternative 20… Nh7 21. Ne4 Qe5 22. Qxh6 Kh8 hadn't actually occurred to me, having planned 20...Nh7 21.Rg6 instead. Whether that would have succeeded I don't know, but I get material instead, so I'm happy.
Probably taking with the Rook is better, since this gives Black the chance to exchange and hopefully take the sting out of my attack.
The Knight has to come over to the K-side to assist in defence.
My King steps forward to allow my other Rook access to the h-file.

Opening up the diagonal again seals Black's fate, though the alternative  24… Rfe8 25. Rh1 f6 26. Rg4 didn't offer much hope. Actually I'd assumed the Knight was headed to f6, and I would have thought that better anyway. Now the game is up...

Now there are mating threats if Black isn't careful; he really can't afford the discovered check and is best allowing the Knight sacrifice with 25 … cxd5 26. Bxd5+ Rf7 27. Rh5, though with the Rook pinned that's pretty much a loser too.
Instead, the KIng comes out, allows the discovered check, with hope of escaping...
But Black soon sees that after 27.Rxg7+ too much material is gone, and here he resigned.
this is, where White usually goes wrong...
White had enough dawn treading: he resigned...
At this stage of the game, I hardly could try to understand that white's attack!
(Ufff, there's something to try here.. mmm... probably I can open one or two rows... now I have that King front of me... mmm who knows?
(It could look like a good performing of the plan...)
My bad move! I did not noted the imminent pawn capture. Oups, like a child...
Here I had my opponent comment: ganburighan: (5 days ago) It is hard to believe such an interesting position arose from a 1. d4 opening! Alan
Black has spoiled a tempo, with a6...
in most variations, Bb4+ can save something: not here...
Black is feeling quite safe here...
u tell me: we won a pawn...
opening up, a whole new game...
things are going wrong, from here...
taking pawn e4, was the least Black could do...
not a sweat broken: not a f*ck given...
Black is going on a fake attack...
but impressive enough to Black: g6 was an option...
from now on, the board is changing rapidly...
no use in Bxb2, Rb1: but this is even worse...
and Black resigned: not overly soon...

This was a tournament game that I started part way through a significant slump in form. By the time this game was fully under way my rating was rising again, albeit slowly. This is one of the games that got me back over 1500 which is into the region that I normally inhabit.

The ending here involved a little luck but was a rather unusual one. 

Please comment and rate this annotation
pins the pawn to the queen to discourage c4
this is a blunder as it loses material
Another blunder which allows me to regain the material I lost earlier
looking to open up the diagonal to h7 after e5
the black king doesn't have much in the way of defence at the moment, the question is can I get rid of the g4 and possibly the h6 pawns
avoids the dangers from n x h6 +
protecting the knight on c3 which later turned out to be critical to the game result

Bd3 doesn't waste the pawn, though black likely trades knight for bishop.
This is a good move.  The threat is black plays e3 and white has no new defense against Nxc2+.  The fork must be defended against, and pushing the knight does that.
Black is probably better off with Nd5.  If I were white I would play BxNa6 and double black's pawns.
This pawn is lost, and black moved it three times.  Better to have taken something for it, like exf3, or bolster its defense with Nf6.
White has moved the bishop to e2 twice.  Each time black moves a pawn, developing position.  Free moves for black.
White is better off playing Bb3, even though it moves the bishop again, because black's best move appear to be trading knight for bishop and doubling white's pawns.
With a bishop move white once again (third time) encourages black to move a pawn.  White's black bishop now has nowhere to run.
